        "content": "# I am handsome\n\nThis note discusses Green's Theorem, a fundamental result in vector calculus that relates a line integral around a simple closed curve to a double integral over the plane region bounded by the curve.\n\n%%WEAVER_CARD_START:Green%%\n%%WEAVER_CARD_END:Green%%\n\nGreen's Theorem states: If \\(C\\) is a positively oriented, piecewise smooth, simple closed curve in the plane and \\(D\\) is the region bounded by \\(C\\), and \\(L\\) and \\(M\\) have continuous partial derivatives on an open region containing \\(D\\), then\n\n\\[\n\\oint_C (L\\,dx + M\\,dy) = \\iint_D \\left( \\frac{\\partial M}{\\partial x} - \\frac{\\partial L}{\\partial y} \\right) dA.\n\\]\n\nThis theorem is a special case of the more general Stokes' theorem and is widely used in physics and engineering."
